ames © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Sublime’; name of a cousin of the Prophet, who married his daughter  Fāṭima  and in  656  became the fourth rightly guided caliph. His sons    Ḥasan    and    Ḥusayn    are regarded by Shiites as Muḥammad's true successors."],"variants":[]},{"name":"\"Bach\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Zachary  , also used as an independent given name."],"variants":[{"name":"Zachary","meanings":["vernacular form of the New Testament Greek name <i>Zacharias</i>, a form of Hebrew   Zechariah   ‘God has remembered’. This was the name of the father of John the Baptist, who underwent a temporary period of dumbness for his lack of faith (Luke 1), and of a more obscure figure, Zacharias son of Barachias, who was slain ‘between the temple and the altar’ (Matthew 23:35; Luke 11:51). In the United States it is familiar as the name of a 19th-century president,  Zachary Taylor . Since the 1990s the name has been remarkably popular in the English-speaking world, especially in the United States."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mali \"Bach\" ferch Hywel was born about 1380, in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the daughter of Gruffudd ap Llywelyn and Nest ferch Ithel. She had at least 1 son with Tudor Ab Ieuan."},"et":{"ABT    1380–":"umbes 1380–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1426–Male":"1426–Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1426":"1426","1396":"1396","A